This paper focuses on the development of a new whole-body control method for achieving dynamic locomotion in humanoid robots and passive-ankle biped robots. The paper discusses the use of model-based walking controllers and the relaxation of contact constraints to reduce jerk during foot contact switching. These topics are all related to robotics and control, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.RO (Robotics) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses uncertainty analysis and experimentation with various locomotion modalities, which could also be relevant to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-categories. The use of a TVR planner for dynamic walking and the analysis of irregular and slippery terrain suggest that the paper could also be relevant to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of a viscoelastic liquid-cooled biped and the potential for image processing for terrain analysis, which could be relevant to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category.
